We have several options available to fulfill your Hart County Primary Voting responsibilities.

You may already visit govoteky.com in order to request a no-excuse absentee ballot to be mailed to your home. Once received you will mark your vote and sign your envelope (for signature verification of identity.) Then you can either mail the envelope back in, or bring it to the courthouse to drop off in the designated ballot box.
If you choose to vote in person, you have two options. You may call 270-524-2751 to make an appointment for voting at the Clerk‚Äôs office between June 8 to June 22. On Primary day the polls will be open at the Hart County Sheriff‚Äôs office. Anyone in Hart County is welcome to come vote on primary day at the Sheriff‚Äôs office, there will be plenty of staff to assist, while maintaining social distancing and sanitizing protocols.

We‚Äôre ready for you to vote Hart County, are you?

Circuit court clerks statewide will resume providing limited driver's license services statewide June 1, the Administrative Office of the Courts announced today. Processing renewals remotely will promote safety by reducing foot traffic at court facilities.

Individuals with a driver‚Äôs license, permit or ID card that expired or was lost between March 1-June 30, 2020, who wish to obtain a renewal or reissuance must apply through a remote application process. Individuals with a driver‚Äôs license, permit or ID card that expired or was lost before March 1, 2020, must obtain new credentials, which will be issued through an in-person visit to an Office of Circuit Court Clerk. Check out details at https://bit.ly/3gEpoYS

May 22 - Restaurants, with limited 33% capacity and outdoor seating (unlimited with adequate spacing)

June 1 - Movie theaters, fitness centers

June 11 - Campgrounds, public and private

June 15 - Child care, with reduced capacity; potentially low-touch and outdoor youth sports

In addition, Gov. Beshear said Phase 3 of the reopening plan is coming July 1, which includes bars (with limitations) and gatherings up to 50 people.

post_text:
After a case is deemed to be positive, Communicable Disease staff from the Barren River District Health Department contact the case (or patient) to conduct a case investigation which includes gaining information about any contacts they have had with people over the past two weeks. If you are a direct contact with the positive case (meaning you have had extended contact with the person) you will be notified directly by a member of the Communicable Disease staff from the health department. We have been preparing for this day.

We must continue to follow recommendations provided by the CDC, the state, Barren River District Health Department, and Governor Andy Beshear of social distancing and good hand hygiene. Practicing social distancing is the most important method for staying healthy. We urge Hart County to stay at home as much as you can, and leave only for essential items such as groceries and medications.

Barren River District Health Department

Hart County Cooperative Extension Service
March 20 at 1:59 PM ¬∑

The Hart County Extension Office will be closed to the public beginning today, March 20, 2020.

üìû Our employees will still be available by phone and email and we look forward to finding new ways to offer you research based information and programming!

We will also continue receiving soil samples for farm, lawn or garden, as long as UK soil testing labs remain open. Just leave them outside our front door and fill out the information on the clipboard in the tote on the front porch. Please make sure the soil is dry.

We apologize for any inconvenience. We realize you are still planning your gardens, caring for your livestock, taking care of your families, watching your money, cooking meals, and more. Please don‚Äôt hesitate to call us or message us on here with any questions you have!

If you need assistance please call the Hart County Extension Office at 270-524-2451 and the answering machine will direct you as to how to get in touch with our office staff.

post_text: Within the Governor‚Äôs March 18th press release, the Department for Community Based Services (DCBS) will extend certification periods for all recipients of all public assistance programs (such as SNAP or formerly food stamps, Medicaid, K-TAP, and State Supplementation) for three months. Those households whose certification periods end in May will automatically be extended to August, June to September, and so on. Job search, work and participation requirements are temporarily suspended for most programs. For further assistance please contact your case worker, or access the benefind website at https://benefind.ky.gov or by calling the DCBS call center at 1-855-306-8959.

post_text: Social distancing importance
shared_text:
Barren River District Health Department
March 16 at 4:36 PM ¬∑

Why is social distancing so important? Social distancing can help slow the spread of #COVID19. This means staying home unless necessary, avoiding crowded places, and maintaining a distance of about 6 feet from others.

Remember, social distancing doesn't mean boredom! Friends and family are still a phone call, Face Time, or text message away. Other ways to pass the time include starting a new book, taking up a hobby like yoga (YouTube has great videos!), or learning how to play an instrument. It is also important to maintain a healthy diet, stay hydrated, and continue physical activity to stay healthy.

For more prevention tips, visit https://bit.ly/2QbLFkW.

#TeamKentucky #TogetherKy

shared_text:
Child Care Aware of Kentucky
March 4 at 8:00 PM ¬∑

Here is some guidance from the Division of Child Care regarding the Coronavirus:
Since there are currently no confirmed cases in Kentucky, the Department of Public Health has not put out any specific information for child care programs on how to stop the spread of the illness. I would encourage you to continue diligent handwashing procedures, particularly when children wipe their noses or use the restroom. Be very careful about children washing their hands before and after Play-Doh or other sensory materials. Make sure to empty your water table more frequently. Other than that, we have no additional updates at this time. The Division of Child Care will let you know if that changes.
The attached poster can also help explain Coronavirus to parents and staff

shared_text:
Paul Grider is with Randy Grimes.
November 12, 2019 at 9:43 PM ¬∑

A Conversation About Addiction....

This Thursday night at 6PM in the cafeteria at Hart County High School we have a public informational meeting concerning addiction in our community. Addiction touches all our lives in some way and we need to know that we are not alone. There are resources out there to help. Join us as we raise awareness of this epidemic and bring to light what is being done to heal it.

I will be the MC of the event. I invite and strongly encourage everyone to attend. There will be informational booths, excellent speakers, a chili supper and door prizes will be given away.
